WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.370 --> 00:00:03.746
Prof: Today I want to
talk about what I think of as

00:00:03.746 --> 00:00:06.206
one of the most significant
failures of environmental law in

00:00:06.206 --> 00:00:07.290
the twentieth century.
 

00:00:07.290 --> 00:00:11.760
And this is the way that we
manage toxic substances.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:15.587
But this is a story that is
more about not just the

00:00:15.587 --> 00:00:20.027
individual chemicals but also
the products that are created

00:00:20.027 --> 00:00:23.090
when chemicals are merged
together,

00:00:23.090 --> 00:00:24.230
they're synthesized.
 

00:00:24.230 --> 00:00:27.550
So what is the plastics problem
?

00:00:27.550 --> 00:00:30.030
In part, it's the enormity of
the industry.

00:00:30.030 --> 00:00:34.986
About 119 billion pounds now
produced each year in the United

00:00:34.986 --> 00:00:35.730
States.
 

00:00:35.730 --> 00:00:39.030
This is roughly about a $400
billion industry.

00:00:39.030 --> 00:00:42.324
And I mentioned earlier that
just to give you a point of

00:00:42.324 --> 00:00:44.720
comparison to the pesticide
industry,

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:48.690
the pesticide industry produces
about ten billion pounds.

00:00:48.690 --> 00:00:52.260
So it's about ten times smaller
than the plastics industry.

00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:56.570
And the annual sales from
pesticides are about ten to

00:00:56.570 --> 00:01:00.548
twelve billion dollars per year
in the nation.

00:01:00.548 --> 00:01:04.528
So compared to the attention
that pesticides have been given

00:01:04.528 --> 00:01:07.159
over the past thirty to forty
years,

00:01:07.159 --> 00:01:10.596
the plastics problem has been
just about fully neglected by

00:01:10.596 --> 00:01:11.250
Congress.
 

00:01:11.250 --> 00:01:15.942
Although it did pass the Toxic
Substance control act back in

00:01:15.942 --> 00:01:16.500
1976.
 

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:20.013
And this law was intended to
encourage premarket testing of

00:01:20.013 --> 00:01:20.739
chemicals.
 

00:01:20.739 --> 00:01:24.572
And what we'll see today is
that the majority of chemicals

00:01:24.572 --> 00:01:27.989
remain untested,
that the ingredients are

00:01:27.989 --> 00:01:30.622
unlabeled,
the country of origin is

00:01:30.622 --> 00:01:32.379
unknown for most products.
 

00:01:32.379 --> 00:01:36.680
The recovery rate is
exceptionally low.

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:40.546
And recycling failure occurs
for many reasons,

00:01:40.546 --> 00:01:45.530
but we'll explore several of
those later in the session.

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:50.410
Environmental contamination at
a global scale has occurred.

00:01:50.410 --> 00:01:54.498
There are plastic particles,
molecules in ambient air

00:01:54.498 --> 00:01:56.230
outside and indoors.
 

00:01:56.230 --> 00:01:59.938
Plastics have contaminated
underground aquifers as well as

00:01:59.938 --> 00:02:03.780
surface waters in many parts of
the industrialized world.

00:02:03.780 --> 00:02:06.578
There's been universal human
exposure.

00:02:06.578 --> 00:02:09.310
That exposure is chronic,
you get it on a daily basis.

00:02:09.310 --> 00:02:14.403
And the health effects that we
now are beginning to understand

00:02:14.403 --> 00:02:19.750
have to do predominately with
endocrine disrupting compounds,

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:23.030
chemicals that are mimicking
human hormones.

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:26.169
We rely, unfortunately,
for the most part on animal

00:02:26.169 --> 00:02:30.061
studies to give us some insight
into what the effects on humans

00:02:30.061 --> 00:02:31.378
are likely to be.
 

00:02:31.378 --> 00:02:35.401
But we rely on that evidence
for many other classes of

00:02:35.401 --> 00:02:36.919
compounds as well.
 

00:02:36.919 --> 00:02:40.675
So this area has received
virtually no attention from the

00:02:40.675 --> 00:02:44.901
Environmental Protection Agency,
and I want to talk a little bit

00:02:44.901 --> 00:02:46.780
today about why that is.
 

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:52.020
So 850,000 people employed in
this industry.

00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:57.508
That number 379 is now up about
$400 billion per year,

00:02:57.508 --> 00:03:01.400
and plastics comprise seventy
percent of the synthetic

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:06.938
chemical industry in the nation,
including 500 different resins.

00:03:06.938 --> 00:03:09.060
Plastics labeling is confusing
to many people.

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:14.144
You may not look on the bottom
of a milk carton or you may not

00:03:14.144 --> 00:03:18.562
look on the back of many
different products to look at

00:03:18.562 --> 00:03:20.479
the recycling code.
 

00:03:20.479 --> 00:03:23.299
The recycling code in the
United States is completely

00:03:23.299 --> 00:03:23.949
voluntary.
 

00:03:23.949 --> 00:03:27.750
There is no legal obligation to
post the chemical content,

00:03:27.750 --> 00:03:31.816
the origin of the plastics or
what should be done with it once

00:03:31.816 --> 00:03:33.750
the product is discarded.
 

00:03:33.750 --> 00:03:36.449
So, give you an example here.
 

00:03:36.449 --> 00:03:40.020
Polyethylene,
PET, has the symbol number one.

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:45.620
So bottled drinks such as Pepsi
and Coca Cola are packaged in

00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:46.180
PET.
 

00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:49.020
Sometimes it's called PETE,
polyethylene.

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:51.840
There's a high-density version
of that, which is number two.

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:53.524
And there's a low density
version of that,

00:03:53.524 --> 00:03:54.470
which is number four.
 

00:03:54.470 --> 00:03:58.169
So carrier bags and bin liners,
for example,

00:03:58.169 --> 00:04:02.211
are the low-density
polyethylene as opposed to say

00:04:02.211 --> 00:04:07.408
the gallon milk jugs which are
the high-density polyethylene.

00:04:07.408 --> 00:04:11.137
The polyethylenes are the most
likely to be recycled among all

00:04:11.137 --> 00:04:11.810
plastics.
 

00:04:11.810 --> 00:04:14.959
Polyvinylchloride,
by comparison,

00:04:14.959 --> 00:04:19.290
PVC for short,
is contained in many different

00:04:19.290 --> 00:04:20.569
products.
 

00:04:20.569 --> 00:04:22.706
Water pipes,
and I'll show you some examples

00:04:22.706 --> 00:04:24.050
of that in a few moments.
 

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:28.434
It's almost never recycled,
which means that it's either

00:04:28.434 --> 00:04:32.660
buried or it's burned once it is
finally discarded.

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:38.043
Polypropylene,
you may find polypropylene in

00:04:38.043 --> 00:04:38.920
rugs.
 

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:41.762
You can find it also in
margarine tubs,

00:04:41.762 --> 00:04:45.129
different kinds of food
packaging products.

00:04:45.129 --> 00:04:48.110
But also in these microwavable
meal trays.

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:51.110
Polystyrene,
most people understand what

00:04:51.110 --> 00:04:52.110
styrene is.
 

00:04:52.110 --> 00:04:54.379
You are all familiar with
styrene balls.

00:04:54.379 --> 00:04:59.242
But it's also an absorbent
material that's put at the base

00:04:59.242 --> 00:05:01.290
of meats in packaging.
 

00:05:01.290 --> 00:05:05.235
And I mentioned to you that the
packaging problem is,

00:05:05.235 --> 00:05:09.180
especially related to food,
is incredibly complex.

00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:11.735
There's no way for you to know
what chemicals are in the

00:05:11.735 --> 00:05:14.338
packaging materials that you buy
in the grocery store.

00:05:14.338 --> 00:05:20.319
Seven is reserved for other
kinds of plastic resins.

00:05:20.319 --> 00:05:23.740
So only those that do not fall
into the other categories are

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:25.189
given the number seven.
 

00:05:25.189 --> 00:05:28.043
And we'll concentrate on one of
those today, which is called

00:05:28.043 --> 00:05:28.720
bisphenol-A.
 

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:32.351
Bisphenol-A is what's used to
form polycarbonate plastic

00:05:32.351 --> 00:05:35.389
that's very dense,
very hard, and often it's in

00:05:35.389 --> 00:05:36.379
clear form.
 

00:05:36.379 --> 00:05:37.079
It can be colored.
 

00:05:37.079 --> 00:05:41.512
So Nalgene bottles are a good
example of number seven,

00:05:41.512 --> 00:05:43.269
the polycarbonates.
 

00:05:43.269 --> 00:05:48.403
And also you might think of the
headlamps on a car or a

00:05:48.403 --> 00:05:51.350
motorcycle helmet or a visor.
 

00:05:51.350 --> 00:05:53.690
These are all examples of
polycarbonate.

00:05:53.690 --> 00:05:59.632
Here is a chart that lists the
recycling rate in yellow for all

00:05:59.632 --> 00:06:02.699
the different classifications.
 

00:06:02.699 --> 00:06:06.730
And you basically see PVCs are
at the bottom of the list.

00:06:06.730 --> 00:06:10.473
So PVCs are not recycled
because the chemical content is

00:06:10.473 --> 00:06:11.629
so complicated.
 

00:06:11.629 --> 00:06:16.800
The highest degree of recycling
occurs with the polyethylenes.

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:20.124
So the PETE bottles have
roughly a twenty to twenty-five

00:06:20.124 --> 00:06:23.569
percent recycling rate on
average in the United States.

00:06:23.569 --> 00:06:26.610
And this is highly variable by
region in the nation.

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:29.410
And also by time of the year.
 

00:06:29.410 --> 00:06:33.569
The polypropylene is almost
never recycled,

00:06:33.569 --> 00:06:35.649
nor is polystyrene.
 

00:06:35.649 --> 00:06:40.386
Polycarbonates,
the hard plastic composite that

00:06:40.386 --> 00:06:43.887
exists, for example,
in my glasses,

00:06:43.887 --> 00:06:48.110
these are also almost never
recycled.

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:49.250
So what happens to them?
 

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:52.413
I'm going to take you on a
quick Cook's Tour of plastic in

00:06:52.413 --> 00:06:53.079
your life.
 

00:06:53.079 --> 00:06:56.017
And you remember that I
challenged you to try to find

00:06:56.017 --> 00:06:59.240
out if you could avoid
purchasing plastics for a week,

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:02.317
and if you are able to do that,
I challenged you to avoid using

00:07:02.317 --> 00:07:03.410
plastics for a week.
 

00:07:03.410 --> 00:07:06.480
And I believe that today is a
virtual impossibility.

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:10.562
So I started to do a little
inventory in my own life and

00:07:10.562 --> 00:07:15.166
actually got quite disturbed at
myself and my own ignorance and

00:07:15.166 --> 00:07:17.839
what I had exposed my family to.
 

00:07:17.839 --> 00:07:22.014
And I became extremely
interested in trying to kind of

00:07:22.014 --> 00:07:26.346
reconstruct why I was so
clueless about the thousands of

00:07:26.346 --> 00:07:31.307
different products that had made
their way into my life and into

00:07:31.307 --> 00:07:33.120
my family's life.
 

00:07:33.120 --> 00:07:35.420
Contact lenses are a good
example.

00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:37.860
There are hard contact lenses
and there are soft contact

00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:38.259
lenses.
 

00:07:38.259 --> 00:07:41.401
The hard lenses could contain
bisphenol-A, it's a

00:07:41.401 --> 00:07:42.449
polycarbonate.
 

00:07:42.449 --> 00:07:46.526
The softer contact lenses that
will change their shape with

00:07:46.526 --> 00:07:50.322
your eye or as they rotate
across a surface that is not

00:07:50.322 --> 00:07:53.954
completely even,
those contact lenses normally

00:07:53.954 --> 00:07:55.440
contain phthalates.
 

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:59.622
Phthalates are softeners,
so bisphenol-A is the hardener,

00:07:59.622 --> 00:08:01.639
phthalates are softeners.
 

00:08:01.639 --> 00:08:05.740
And these phthalates are a
particular problem with respect

00:08:05.740 --> 00:08:09.122
to one, which is called diethyl
phthalate, DEHP,

00:08:09.122 --> 00:08:12.290
that I'll talk about a little
bit later.

00:08:12.290 --> 00:08:15.160
My daughter wears a retainer.
 

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:17.779
She's ten years old,
my youngest daughter.

00:08:17.779 --> 00:08:19.730
And I don't know what's in that.
 

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:22.170
But I would imagine that it's
predominately polycarbonate.

00:08:22.170 --> 00:08:26.329
She wears it about twelve to
fifteen hours per day.

00:08:26.329 --> 00:08:29.899
And also, most people have
dental sealants.

00:08:29.899 --> 00:08:31.920
Dental sealants are pretty
interesting.

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:36.421
So that you can test people's
saliva after the dental sealants

00:08:36.421 --> 00:08:40.850
are put in and you can find the
bisphenol-A in the saliva.

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:45.136
Also, there's a protective
characteristic of these

00:08:45.136 --> 00:08:46.100
sealants.
 

00:08:46.100 --> 00:08:49.202
They prevent you from getting
cavities that would demand

00:08:49.202 --> 00:08:52.303
putting a different kind of
plastic into your tooth or a

00:08:52.303 --> 00:08:53.320
metal amalgam.
 

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:56.700
And many people in my
generation and my parents'

00:08:56.700 --> 00:09:00.871
generation have fillings in
their mouths that include metal

00:09:00.871 --> 00:09:04.076
amalgams,
including compounds such as

00:09:04.076 --> 00:09:04.808
mercury.
 

00:09:04.808 --> 00:09:07.778
So it's a very interesting kind
of a tradeoff one might make.

00:09:07.778 --> 00:09:12.918
Think about different other
sources of plastic in your life.

00:09:12.918 --> 00:09:15.572
Most of you are probably
familiar with that smell of the

00:09:15.572 --> 00:09:18.514
vinyl shower curtain when you
first open the package and for a

00:09:18.514 --> 00:09:21.070
couple of days it's off gassing
in your bathroom.

00:09:21.070 --> 00:09:24.255
Different kinds of clothing,
raincoats, fabrics,

00:09:24.255 --> 00:09:27.442
GORE-TEX, for example,
are made out of different

00:09:27.442 --> 00:09:28.730
plastic resins.
 

00:09:28.730 --> 00:09:33.850
And these also are generally
non-recyclable.

00:09:33.850 --> 00:09:36.100
And I want you to think about
the built environment.

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:39.251
When a house is built in the
Northeastern part of the U.S.,

00:09:39.251 --> 00:09:41.210
it's generally framed out of
wood.

00:09:41.210 --> 00:09:44.509
You see the plywood there
that's being tacked onto these

00:09:44.509 --> 00:09:46.370
two by fours or two by sixes.
 

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:50.676
And then you see the plastic
sheathing that is being attached

00:09:50.676 --> 00:09:52.830
made by DuPont called Tyvek.
 

00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:59.649
Tyvek is an interesting product
in that it seals the house from

00:09:59.649 --> 00:10:00.418
mold.
 

00:10:00.418 --> 00:10:04.446
And that also has a protective
effect in that molds are known

00:10:04.446 --> 00:10:08.404
to threaten human health and
induce asthma or exacerbate it,

00:10:08.404 --> 00:10:09.678
as one example.
 

00:10:09.678 --> 00:10:13.200
But this product also is
extremely rarely recycled.

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:17.908
Tyvek also you can find in a
variety of different settings.

00:10:17.908 --> 00:10:22.211
Here's a Tyvek disposable
coverall that is claimed by the

00:10:22.211 --> 00:10:26.283
corporation to protect against
more than 150 hazardous

00:10:26.283 --> 00:10:27.360
chemicals.
 

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:30.000
So for those people that work
with hazardous chemicals,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.250
here's a product that helps to
protect them.

00:10:32.250 --> 00:10:36.178
The idea of it being disposable
caught my attention.

00:10:36.178 --> 00:10:37.860
It's advertised as being
disposable.

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:40.381
Certainly most things are
disposable, but that doesn't

00:10:40.381 --> 00:10:43.238
give you any clue about where
they might end up eventually in

00:10:43.238 --> 00:10:44.190
the environment.
 

00:10:44.190 --> 00:10:47.394
In this case,
this will not break down for

00:10:47.394 --> 00:10:50.990
probably hundreds if not
thousands of years.

00:10:50.990 --> 00:10:52.480
Now think about a house.
 

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:56.408
This house has plastic in many
different areas.

00:10:56.408 --> 00:10:59.192
It's got vinyl siding on it,
it has pillars,

00:10:59.192 --> 00:11:03.139
you can see pillars here on the
front and over on the side.

00:11:03.139 --> 00:11:05.634
You might think those pillars
are formed out of wood or

00:11:05.634 --> 00:11:08.500
perhaps that they're ceramic,
but they're generally plastic.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:11.788
You see the light post,
that's plastic as well.

00:11:11.788 --> 00:11:16.667
You see the railing on top of
the front porch near the front

00:11:16.667 --> 00:11:17.658
door here.
 

00:11:17.658 --> 00:11:22.500
This is also probably a
polyvinylchloride plastic.

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:24.778
Also the doors are commonly
plastic.

00:11:24.778 --> 00:11:27.340
The windows,
the window frames are plastic.

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:28.950
And how do they seal?
 

00:11:28.950 --> 00:11:32.434
When your door shuts,
it doesn't shut with hard

00:11:32.434 --> 00:11:36.681
plastic meeting hard plastic,
it's got a separate liner that

00:11:36.681 --> 00:11:40.264
lies next to the door that will
absorb the shock and also it

00:11:40.264 --> 00:11:42.389
will prevent heat from escaping.
 

00:11:42.389 --> 00:11:46.240
So generally with a window,
you'll have several different

00:11:46.240 --> 00:11:48.990
kinds of plastic,
the same with doors.

00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:53.240
The vent that you see up here
near the peak of the roof also

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:54.610
would be plastic.
 

00:11:54.610 --> 00:11:58.457
So that the exterior surfaces
of this structure are

00:11:58.457 --> 00:12:01.230
predominately made out of
plastic.

00:12:01.230 --> 00:12:04.149
Many paints also contain
plastics within them.

00:12:04.149 --> 00:12:09.870
Think also about cord or wire.
 

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:14.668
Wire is generally coated with
vinyl, polyvinylchloride.

00:12:14.668 --> 00:12:18.996
And just as an example,
there are, in a new building

00:12:18.996 --> 00:12:22.325
like Kroon Hall,
where I've got my office,

00:12:22.325 --> 00:12:26.577
there are probably hundreds of
miles of electrical conduit that

00:12:26.577 --> 00:12:29.460
circulate through that single
building.

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:34.048
And then think about power
lines and the sheathing that

00:12:34.048 --> 00:12:36.428
exists on the power lines.
 

00:12:36.428 --> 00:12:39.923
Well how many miles of power
line do you think there are in

00:12:39.923 --> 00:12:41.129
the United States?
 

00:12:41.129 --> 00:12:44.958
Well, one thing you could do is
you could just calculate on

00:12:44.958 --> 00:12:47.221
Google,
type in number of miles of

00:12:47.221 --> 00:12:51.014
roads in the United States,
because most roads are also

00:12:51.014 --> 00:12:53.019
corridors for power lines.
 

00:12:53.019 --> 00:12:56.509
So I would estimate that we
probably have hundreds of

00:12:56.509 --> 00:13:00.134
billions of miles of electrical
cable that's sheeted in

00:13:00.134 --> 00:13:03.759
polyvinylchloride,
all of which is not recyclable.

00:13:03.759 --> 00:13:07.071
Interestingly,
the value of copper inside the

00:13:07.071 --> 00:13:10.759
wire is high enough to encourage
its recycling.

00:13:10.759 --> 00:13:13.639
But the value of the PVC is
negligible.

00:13:13.639 --> 00:13:18.970
Now I'd also like you to think
about your own water supply.

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:20.408
Think about where you grew up.
 

00:13:20.408 --> 00:13:22.250
Do you know where your water
came from?

00:13:22.250 --> 00:13:25.918
Do you know how it was piped to
your facets?

00:13:25.918 --> 00:13:29.375
Well, here's an example of a
water supply being fed by copper

00:13:29.375 --> 00:13:30.470
pipes at the top.
 

00:13:30.470 --> 00:13:34.629
And then there's a distribution
network throughout the house,

00:13:34.629 --> 00:13:38.399
going to say the refrigerator
or going to the kitchen sink,

00:13:38.399 --> 00:13:41.298
going to toilets in different
parts of the house.

00:13:41.298 --> 00:13:45.110
Well this also is made out of
plastic.

00:13:45.110 --> 00:13:48.938
And one would think that
somebody would have demanded

00:13:48.938 --> 00:13:53.211
that these chemicals be tested
to understand whether or not

00:13:53.211 --> 00:13:56.009
they would leach out of the
lines.

00:13:56.009 --> 00:13:58.519
And in many cases,
particularly with newer houses,

00:13:58.519 --> 00:14:00.259
you'll have a filtration
system.

00:14:00.259 --> 00:14:03.000
And you may have seen these
cartridge filtration systems.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:04.210
They look like canisters.
 

00:14:04.210 --> 00:14:05.870
They come in various sizes.
 

00:14:05.870 --> 00:14:09.000
I've got one in my house that's
a sediment filter as one

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:09.570
example.
 

00:14:09.570 --> 00:14:13.226
And it was put in before I
understood this whole plastics

00:14:13.226 --> 00:14:13.750
issue.
 

00:14:13.750 --> 00:14:16.692
And I also can tell you that
it's almost impossible to find a

00:14:16.692 --> 00:14:18.950
water filter that's not made out
of plastic.

00:14:18.950 --> 00:14:22.269
So within this plastic
canister, it's got a top that

00:14:22.269 --> 00:14:23.048
screws on.
 

00:14:23.048 --> 00:14:27.174
So to change the filtration you
take the filter material out and

00:14:27.174 --> 00:14:31.168
then you put a new one in after
a certain number of months.

00:14:31.168 --> 00:14:35.950
So that most water filters also
are plastic.

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:37.961
Also, nobody asked the
question, well,

00:14:37.961 --> 00:14:41.058
what's leaching out of the
filters into the water line?

00:14:41.058 --> 00:14:43.730
Now I'd like you to think about
the vehicle environment.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:45.399
It's kind of interesting.
 

00:14:45.399 --> 00:14:48.105
I use the phrase that people
are spending in the United

00:14:48.105 --> 00:14:50.710
States about ninety percent of
their time indoors.

00:14:50.710 --> 00:14:53.943
Well it's about eighty-seven
percent of their time indoors

00:14:53.943 --> 00:14:57.121
and it's about three to four
percent of their time within

00:14:57.121 --> 00:14:57.860
vehicles.
 

00:14:57.860 --> 00:15:00.658
And think about the interior
cabins.

00:15:00.658 --> 00:15:05.120
On the upper left here,
a new vehicle,

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:08.827
so that this probably has maybe
a couple of dozen different

00:15:08.827 --> 00:15:12.203
polymers in it,
ranging from the TV screen and

00:15:12.203 --> 00:15:16.207
all of its components down
through the plastic steering

00:15:16.207 --> 00:15:18.456
wheel,
plastic dashboard,

00:15:18.456 --> 00:15:21.720
the plastic console between the
seats.

00:15:21.720 --> 00:15:24.822
Different kinds of plastics in
the seat itself,

00:15:24.822 --> 00:15:27.991
including the polyurethane foam
inside the seat,

00:15:27.991 --> 00:15:30.690
almost none of which are
recyclable.

00:15:30.690 --> 00:15:34.027
So eventually most of these
parts that are made out of

00:15:34.027 --> 00:15:36.610
plastic are simply going to be
burned,

00:15:36.610 --> 00:15:40.466
which gives off quite a bit of
energy in an incinerator because

00:15:40.466 --> 00:15:43.080
of a high carbon content in the
plastic.

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:46.899
So remember that most of these
plastics are derived from what?

00:15:46.899 --> 00:15:48.548
They're petroleum-based.
 

00:15:48.548 --> 00:15:55.322
So that it's very important to
recall that fossil fuels,

00:15:55.322 --> 00:16:00.740
oil is the predominant source
of plastics.

00:16:00.740 --> 00:16:04.605
The interior of a subway or in
this case, and Amtrak train on

00:16:04.605 --> 00:16:07.568
the upper right,
also is predominantly plastic,

00:16:07.568 --> 00:16:10.340
as is the interior of an
airline cabin.

00:16:10.340 --> 00:16:15.394
And this is all for an
interesting and really important

00:16:15.394 --> 00:16:16.330
purpose.
 

00:16:16.330 --> 00:16:18.548
And that is to lighten the
weight of the vehicle.

00:16:18.548 --> 00:16:20.792
So thirty years ago,
vehicles were much heavier than

00:16:20.792 --> 00:16:21.538
they are today.
 

00:16:21.538 --> 00:16:26.240
So an average vehicle today
might be 2,500 pounds,

00:16:26.240 --> 00:16:32.092
but an average vehicle perhaps
forty years ago was perhaps 300

00:16:32.092 --> 00:16:35.259
or 400 pounds more than that.
 

00:16:35.259 --> 00:16:38.875
Indeed, there are about 300
pounds of plastic in every new

00:16:38.875 --> 00:16:39.509
vehicle.
 

00:16:39.509 --> 00:16:42.720
And it's pretty much guaranteed
that that material would not be

00:16:42.720 --> 00:16:43.288
recycled.
 

00:16:43.288 --> 00:16:46.355
Also, I'd like you to think
about coatings,

00:16:46.355 --> 00:16:48.908
the whole idea of coating
things.

00:16:48.908 --> 00:16:54.467
I realized that fairly late in
my career that I hadn't paid any

00:16:54.467 --> 00:16:56.620
attention to coatings.
 

00:16:56.620 --> 00:16:59.528
But if you think about the
number of buildings that exist

00:16:59.528 --> 00:17:01.710
in the world,
the number of buildings in the

00:17:01.710 --> 00:17:03.918
United States,
think like say Sherwin

00:17:03.918 --> 00:17:05.950
Williams, the paint industry.
 

00:17:05.950 --> 00:17:08.130
You know what their phrase is?
 

00:17:08.130 --> 00:17:09.970
You know what their corporate
motto is?

00:17:09.970 --> 00:17:12.308
Their corporate motto is
"Cover the Earth."

00:17:12.308 --> 00:17:16.497
And you see this red paint,
their symbol is red paint that

00:17:16.497 --> 00:17:19.730
is flowing down across the top
of a globe.

00:17:19.730 --> 00:17:23.450
Well, think about the surface
area simply of this room.

00:17:23.450 --> 00:17:25.868
Think about the surface area in
your house.

00:17:25.868 --> 00:17:28.538
The flooring,
think about the walls,

00:17:28.538 --> 00:17:30.519
think about the ceiling.
 

00:17:30.519 --> 00:17:32.824
And if you're an executive for
a paint company,

00:17:32.824 --> 00:17:35.428
you're thinking "Oh my
gosh, we have such a huge

00:17:35.428 --> 00:17:35.980
market.
 

00:17:35.980 --> 00:17:38.589
Everybody is going to want to
paint something a different

00:17:38.589 --> 00:17:40.890
color,
and should we make the paints

00:17:40.890 --> 00:17:44.652
to be more stable or not quite
as stable so that they would

00:17:44.652 --> 00:17:48.348
want to repaint after a certain
number of years?"

00:17:48.348 --> 00:17:51.671
So just as another example,
I've done this myself,

00:17:51.671 --> 00:17:54.788
I've refinished floors,
which is a pretty nasty

00:17:54.788 --> 00:17:55.670
business.
 

00:17:55.670 --> 00:17:59.234
You don't want to spend much of
your life refinishing a floor,

00:17:59.234 --> 00:18:02.450
especially if you are dressed
such as this gentleman is,

00:18:02.450 --> 00:18:03.970
with no respirator on.
 

00:18:03.970 --> 00:18:07.335
Because he's breathing in a
pretty nasty mixture of dusts

00:18:07.335 --> 00:18:09.980
that include of course the wood
flooring,

00:18:09.980 --> 00:18:13.550
but it also includes the
plastic, the polyurethanes that

00:18:13.550 --> 00:18:15.368
are put down on the floor.
 

00:18:15.368 --> 00:18:17.140
You can see them right here up
on the podium.

00:18:17.140 --> 00:18:20.163
You can see the shiny coating
on top of the desk,

00:18:20.163 --> 00:18:23.626
and you can see it also on the
desks on the side of your

00:18:23.626 --> 00:18:24.318
chairs.
 

00:18:24.318 --> 00:18:27.874
So that the number of surface
coatings in the world is

00:18:27.874 --> 00:18:31.094
enormous in area,
and we don't really think about

00:18:31.094 --> 00:18:33.710
the long-term consequences of
that.

00:18:33.710 --> 00:18:36.420
What would happen if we didn't
coat these surfaces?

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:38.539
What would happen to the floor?
 

00:18:38.539 --> 00:18:39.848
I mean, could you wash it?
 

00:18:39.848 --> 00:18:45.497
Could you not put a coating
like polyurethane or varnish on

00:18:45.497 --> 00:18:47.250
walls like this?
 

00:18:47.250 --> 00:18:50.650
Would they decay or break down
more quickly?

00:18:50.650 --> 00:18:52.279
And the answer is, no.
 

00:18:52.279 --> 00:18:55.981
And I've been wondering about
that and I've been wondering

00:18:55.981 --> 00:18:58.970
about the origin or aesthetic of
smoothness.

00:18:58.970 --> 00:19:02.390
We love smooth things,
whether or not it's skin,

00:19:02.390 --> 00:19:04.720
whether or not it's a surface.
 

00:19:04.720 --> 00:19:08.740
If something is rough and harsh
then it has a negative attitude

00:19:08.740 --> 00:19:09.519
toward it.
 

00:19:09.519 --> 00:19:12.375
So if you're in the business of
making these coatings,

00:19:12.375 --> 00:19:13.400
you play on that.
 

00:19:13.400 --> 00:19:16.239
Also, if you're in the business
of selling cosmetics,

00:19:16.239 --> 00:19:17.549
you also play on that.
 

00:19:17.549 --> 00:19:20.528
What about other sources?
 

00:19:20.528 --> 00:19:22.240
I've mentioned fragrances in
the past.

00:19:22.240 --> 00:19:26.386
These two contain plasticizers,
diethyl phthalate has been

00:19:26.386 --> 00:19:30.607
found in a number of common
perfumes as well as in some air

00:19:30.607 --> 00:19:31.700
fresheners.
 

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:35.019
And also, think about other
kinds of products in your life.

00:19:35.019 --> 00:19:37.250
Now why is a diaper absorbent?
 

00:19:37.250 --> 00:19:39.858
Why is a personal hygiene
product absorbent?

00:19:39.858 --> 00:19:42.920
Well this diaper has probably
two or three different kinds of

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:43.940
plastic within it.
 

00:19:43.940 --> 00:19:46.318
And what's going to happen to
this?

00:19:46.318 --> 00:19:48.009
Well certainly,
it's not going to be recycled.

00:19:48.009 --> 00:19:50.089
It's likely to be burned or
buried.

00:19:50.089 --> 00:19:53.630
Think about where you sleep.
 

00:19:53.630 --> 00:19:55.568
What is your mattress made out
of?

00:19:55.568 --> 00:19:59.000
Anybody here know exactly what
your mattress is made out of?

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:03.558
Well, it's a very difficult
thing to discover.

00:20:03.558 --> 00:20:06.917
Again, there's no requirement
to label the content of your

00:20:06.917 --> 00:20:08.450
mattress or your pillow.
 

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:13.348
You get a broad description of
it, like polyester filled,

00:20:13.348 --> 00:20:17.635
polyurethane foam,
but you really don't know what

00:20:17.635 --> 00:20:22.368
the environmental fate of these
compounds might be.

00:20:22.368 --> 00:20:25.876
So what I'm doing is I'm
painting a picture for you here

00:20:25.876 --> 00:20:29.430
that we're all as innocent,
you're all as innocent as I am

00:20:29.430 --> 00:20:31.338
in thinking that,
well, somebody must have been

00:20:31.338 --> 00:20:32.118
paying attention to this.
 

00:20:32.118 --> 00:20:36.170
Nobody would really want us to
be lying with our noses within a

00:20:36.170 --> 00:20:40.220
half an inch of a surface where
we had no understanding of what

00:20:40.220 --> 00:20:42.049
the chemical content is.
 

00:20:42.049 --> 00:20:43.660
Think about toys.
 

00:20:43.660 --> 00:20:46.383
Ninety percent of the toys
produced in the world now,

00:20:46.383 --> 00:20:49.316
between eighty percent and
ninety percent are produced in

00:20:49.316 --> 00:20:49.838
China.
 

00:20:49.838 --> 00:20:52.920
And increasingly,
they are made out of plastic.

00:20:52.920 --> 00:20:56.904
You know, consider yourself to
be the executive of McDonald's

00:20:56.904 --> 00:21:00.890
and you're thinking about the
introduction of a new meal,

00:21:00.890 --> 00:21:05.946
a new supersized meal or maybe
an environmentally responsible

00:21:05.946 --> 00:21:07.380
downsized meal.
 

00:21:07.380 --> 00:21:08.680
What are you going to do?
 

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:11.401
Well, one of the first things
you're going to do is you're

00:21:11.401 --> 00:21:14.170
going to try to contract out
with a toy manufacturer to try

00:21:14.170 --> 00:21:17.179
to figure out what the next toy
is going to be that you're going

00:21:17.179 --> 00:21:19.278
to give for free so all the
children,

00:21:19.278 --> 00:21:22.294
when they come to McDonald's,
will sit and play with the toy

00:21:22.294 --> 00:21:23.980
while they eat their hamburger.
 

00:21:23.980 --> 00:21:26.460
Well, what happens to those
toys?

00:21:26.460 --> 00:21:30.461
The overwhelming majority of
them get discarded within a week

00:21:30.461 --> 00:21:32.130
of when they're issued.
 

00:21:32.130 --> 00:21:35.250
And these also are not recycled.
 

00:21:35.250 --> 00:21:37.806
Think about your own
entertainment,

00:21:37.806 --> 00:21:39.308
what you purchase.
 

00:21:39.308 --> 00:21:42.181
And by the way,
all of these toys are wrapped

00:21:42.181 --> 00:21:44.269
in plastic of different forms.
 

00:21:44.269 --> 00:21:46.626
And think about the
polycarbonate CD disc,

00:21:46.626 --> 00:21:50.192
the number of CD discs that you
have lying around your house or

00:21:50.192 --> 00:21:52.318
your apartment or your dorm
room.

00:21:52.318 --> 00:21:55.380
And think about how you bought
it?

00:21:55.380 --> 00:21:58.130
Well, it came in a cover that
looked something like this.

00:21:58.130 --> 00:22:01.866
And it probably was also
wrapped in some other additional

00:22:01.866 --> 00:22:05.688
kind of a vinyl coating,
plastic coating on the outside

00:22:05.688 --> 00:22:09.390
that makes it actually difficult
to get the disc out,

00:22:09.390 --> 00:22:12.368
at least in the store in an
unobtrusive manner.

00:22:12.368 --> 00:22:15.588
So think about your iPhones,
think about your iPods,

00:22:15.588 --> 00:22:18.998
think about your computers,
think about your electronic

00:22:18.998 --> 00:22:19.630
world.
 

00:22:19.630 --> 00:22:22.048
I want to talk a little bit
more about food.

00:22:22.048 --> 00:22:24.032
Because food,
as it turns out,

00:22:24.032 --> 00:22:27.796
is now believed to be the
predominant source of chemical

00:22:27.796 --> 00:22:32.380
components in plastic that are
now measurable in human tissues.

00:22:32.380 --> 00:22:36.834
And I'd like you to think also
about the way that we store

00:22:36.834 --> 00:22:39.248
food,
the way that we buy food,

00:22:39.248 --> 00:22:43.538
the way that it's processed and
how it's packaged and sold.

00:22:43.538 --> 00:22:47.430
And it's done in very specific
ways to promote its freshness

00:22:47.430 --> 00:22:50.726
and to avoid food-borne
illnesses, and this is very

00:22:50.726 --> 00:22:51.650
important.
 

00:22:51.650 --> 00:22:56.156
But we haven't been thinking
ecologically about how to manage

00:22:56.156 --> 00:22:59.855
this problem,
because really no one has

00:22:59.855 --> 00:23:05.643
designed these products so that
the end of the life fate is

00:23:05.643 --> 00:23:07.640
being considered.
 

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:13.046
Indeed, no producer really has
responsibility for disposal or

00:23:13.046 --> 00:23:16.200
the ultimate fate of the
product.

00:23:16.200 --> 00:23:19.240
Think also about your
electronic world with respect to

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:19.930
computers.
 

00:23:19.930 --> 00:23:24.952
I became fascinated when I read
that a printer I was using had

00:23:24.952 --> 00:23:25.940
ink in it.
 

00:23:25.940 --> 00:23:27.625
And the ink,
I mean obviously,

00:23:27.625 --> 00:23:30.650
the printer is formed
predominately out of plastic or

00:23:30.650 --> 00:23:33.731
different kinds of plastics,
including the electronics

00:23:33.731 --> 00:23:34.430
board.
 

00:23:34.430 --> 00:23:38.640
But I didn't know that the ink
itself could have plastic in it.

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:40.730
Why would ink have plastic in
it?

00:23:40.730 --> 00:23:43.769
Well, it turns out that the
plastic in bisphenol-A has an

00:23:43.769 --> 00:23:47.190
effect on paper that it prevents
the ink from spreading into the

00:23:47.190 --> 00:23:49.470
fibers of the paper once it's
applied.

00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:55.335
This is apparently more common
with the inkjet printers or the

00:23:55.335 --> 00:24:01.200
heat-driven printers that you
get as a credit card receipt.

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:07.348
Think also about bisphenol-A
and polycarbonates and the next

00:24:07.348 --> 00:24:12.038
generation of water bottles and
containers.

00:24:12.038 --> 00:24:17.780
So that many people have
recognized now that when infants

00:24:17.780 --> 00:24:22.532
are fed formula,
it's very common for a mom or a

00:24:22.532 --> 00:24:25.880
dad or whoever to fill up a
bottle,

00:24:25.880 --> 00:24:28.286
a plastic bottle,
either with hot water or to put

00:24:28.286 --> 00:24:29.390
it in the microwave.
 

00:24:29.390 --> 00:24:35.215
So that the idea that heating
of these products could energize

00:24:35.215 --> 00:24:41.232
the molecules and cause some of
them to migrate into the food or

00:24:41.232 --> 00:24:44.838
the liquid itself,
this was not tested.

00:24:44.838 --> 00:24:47.442
It was not required to be
tested in a sufficient way by

00:24:47.442 --> 00:24:49.130
the Food and Drug
Administration.

00:24:49.130 --> 00:24:51.614
Although the Food and Drug
Administration has the legal

00:24:51.614 --> 00:24:52.578
authority to do so.
 

00:24:52.578 --> 00:24:55.450
So what I'm doing is painting a
picture here that the

00:24:55.450 --> 00:24:58.540
Environmental Protection Agency
has the responsibility to

00:24:58.540 --> 00:25:01.078
implement the Toxic Substance
Control Act.

00:25:01.078 --> 00:25:03.578
They have not required prior
testing.

00:25:03.578 --> 00:25:08.019
They have not demanded that
hazardous components,

00:25:08.019 --> 00:25:11.267
those chemicals that are found
to adversely affect the health

00:25:11.267 --> 00:25:13.503
of other species,
that they be eliminated from

00:25:13.503 --> 00:25:14.038
the product.
 

00:25:14.038 --> 00:25:19.420
And there's no labeling
involved, either in the country

00:25:19.420 --> 00:25:25.200
of origin or in the chemical
composition of the product.

00:25:25.200 --> 00:25:28.618
So there's absolutely no way
that the consumer has to

00:25:28.618 --> 00:25:32.236
discriminate between a safe or
unsafe or environmentally

00:25:32.236 --> 00:25:33.880
responsible products.
 

00:25:33.880 --> 00:25:36.914
Also, I want you to think a
little bit more about what we

00:25:36.914 --> 00:25:37.618
drink from.
 

00:25:37.618 --> 00:25:42.311
And many of these containers
have some fibers,

00:25:42.311 --> 00:25:44.920
plant material in them.
 

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:47.940
But they are often coated with
plastic as well.

00:25:47.940 --> 00:25:50.608
This is a typical grocery store.
 

00:25:50.608 --> 00:25:52.996
And the next time you walk into
a supermarket,

00:25:52.996 --> 00:25:54.798
I hope you walk down the
aisles.

00:25:54.798 --> 00:25:58.498
And I want you to pay special
attention and look particularly

00:25:58.498 --> 00:26:01.826
for products that are not
wrapped in plastic or they're

00:26:01.826 --> 00:26:04.230
not stored in plastic
environments.

00:26:04.230 --> 00:26:08.519
The same thing goes with
respect to Coke.

00:26:08.519 --> 00:26:11.950
I gave a lecture similar to
this several months ago.

00:26:11.950 --> 00:26:13.910
And I was struck.
 

00:26:13.910 --> 00:26:17.972
A gentleman came up after the
lecture, he was a very heavyset

00:26:17.972 --> 00:26:18.380
guy.
 

00:26:18.380 --> 00:26:21.505
And he said,
"I drink three to four

00:26:21.505 --> 00:26:24.150
liters of soda every day."
 

00:26:24.150 --> 00:26:26.960
And he said,
"From what you said,

00:26:26.960 --> 00:26:30.009
I'm worried about the plastic
chemicals migrating into the

00:26:30.009 --> 00:26:33.380
liquids and whether or not it's
building up in my body."

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:35.291
I'm thinking,
oh, three to four liters of

00:26:35.291 --> 00:26:36.009
soda per day.
 

00:26:36.009 --> 00:26:39.578
That's not good with respect to
