00:26:54.193 --> 00:26:57.730
the Coke out of these liter
bottles that are made out of

00:26:57.730 --> 00:26:59.210
polyethylene."
 

00:26:59.210 --> 00:27:01.383
Well I said to him,
I thought for a couple of

00:27:01.383 --> 00:27:03.607
minutes and I said,
"Well, you know,

00:27:03.607 --> 00:27:06.319
I think I would avoid the cans
because at least the

00:27:06.319 --> 00:27:09.574
polyethylene does not have a
hormonally active compound in it

00:27:09.574 --> 00:27:10.930
such as bisphenol-A.
 

00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:13.710
Well he was not pleased about
the story.

00:27:13.710 --> 00:27:17.150
But it gives you some insight
into the way that the epoxy

00:27:17.150 --> 00:27:20.773
resins are being used in order
to prevent oxidization on the

00:27:20.773 --> 00:27:22.740
inside of all sorts of cans.
 

00:27:22.740 --> 00:27:25.538
Canned tomatoes,
think about your dining hall,

00:27:25.538 --> 00:27:27.318
any of you work in the dining
hall,

00:27:27.318 --> 00:27:32.208
think about the large cans that
they have their food delivered

00:27:32.208 --> 00:27:32.930
within.
 

00:27:32.930 --> 00:27:37.298
And all these are potential
sources of exposure.

00:27:37.298 --> 00:27:41.078
Think of the way that meats are
packaged, that are wrapped in

00:27:41.078 --> 00:27:44.480
vinyl that are sitting on
polystyrene, none of which is

00:27:44.480 --> 00:27:45.298
recycled.
 

00:27:45.298 --> 00:27:46.960
What happens when you get your
food home?

00:27:46.960 --> 00:27:48.650
Well, you bring it into a
refrigerator.

00:27:48.650 --> 00:27:49.680
And where do you store it?
 

00:27:49.680 --> 00:27:52.048
You store it inside plastic
bins.

00:27:52.048 --> 00:27:57.078
And my refrigerator looks quite
a bit like this.

00:27:57.078 --> 00:28:02.150
And what I am not showing you
here is the water supply.

00:28:02.150 --> 00:28:07.181
So that some refrigerators have
a little interior cut out in the

00:28:07.181 --> 00:28:11.893
front door where you push a
glass into it to get fresh water

00:28:11.893 --> 00:28:14.210
or it's an ice dispenser.
 

00:28:14.210 --> 00:28:18.664
So that tracing the origin of
the water to that will lead you

00:28:18.664 --> 00:28:21.635
to plastic tubing,
which is made out of a

00:28:21.635 --> 00:28:24.308
phthalate, could be bisphenol-A.
 

00:28:24.308 --> 00:28:26.530
What happens to all these
products once we get rid of

00:28:26.530 --> 00:28:26.828
them?
 

00:28:26.828 --> 00:28:29.936
Well, it's kind of ironic that
we take them out and we put them

00:28:29.936 --> 00:28:31.190
in a plastic trash bin.
 

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:34.884
I just walked in past
Vanderbilt Hall and you all know

00:28:34.884 --> 00:28:35.858
the walkway.
 

00:28:35.858 --> 00:28:39.722
And there are about fifteen or
twenty different plastic garbage

00:28:39.722 --> 00:28:40.970
cans all lined up.
 

00:28:40.970 --> 00:28:42.680
What happens to those when they
crack?

00:28:42.680 --> 00:28:44.598
Where do they end up?
 

00:28:44.598 --> 00:28:49.316
Similarly, most will end up
either underground or they will

00:28:49.316 --> 00:28:51.349
end up in incinerators.
 

00:28:51.349 --> 00:28:53.000
Think about sports.
 

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:54.880
I was thinking about Lindsey
Vonn.

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:58.682
And as I was skiing over
Christmas break,

00:28:58.682 --> 00:29:02.960
I thought about my own gear
that I have on.

00:29:02.960 --> 00:29:05.880
I had plastic skis on,
I had plastic boots on,

00:29:05.880 --> 00:29:08.180
I had a plastic polycarbonate
helmet on,

00:29:08.180 --> 00:29:11.240
I had plastic goggles on,
on top of my polycarbonate

00:29:11.240 --> 00:29:12.259
plastic lenses.
 

00:29:12.259 --> 00:29:16.576
I had a Gortex jacket on,
I had waterproof pants on that

00:29:16.576 --> 00:29:21.048
not only were synthetic and
formed at least in part out of

00:29:21.048 --> 00:29:23.961
plastic,
but they also had been applied

00:29:23.961 --> 00:29:27.618
with a waterproofing agent that
we talked about earlier,

00:29:27.618 --> 00:29:33.227
a compound that basically is
designed to prevent molecules

00:29:33.227 --> 00:29:35.490
from resting on them.
 

00:29:35.490 --> 00:29:37.913
So that they shed water,
they shed stains,

00:29:37.913 --> 00:29:39.568
stain-resistant chemicals.
 

00:29:39.568 --> 00:29:45.029
And also, I had underwear that
was long underwear that was made

00:29:45.029 --> 00:29:46.440
out of fleece.
 

00:29:46.440 --> 00:29:48.880
Fleece is polyethylene often.
 

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:51.380
And fleece actually can be
recycled,

00:29:51.380 --> 00:29:53.940
so that some people claim,
such as Patagonia,

00:29:53.940 --> 00:29:56.000
that they use a certain
percentage of recycled

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.430
polyethylene when they make some
of their products.

00:29:58.430 --> 00:30:02.786
The poles themselves are made
often out of plastic,

00:30:02.786 --> 00:30:06.009
as are the handles and the
baskets.

00:30:06.009 --> 00:30:10.491
So that just about any sport
you can imagine is now dependent

00:30:10.491 --> 00:30:12.509
quite heavily on plastic.
 

00:30:12.509 --> 00:30:16.107
The sleds that they use,
the sled that won the Games the

00:30:16.107 --> 00:30:17.808
other night for the U.S.
 

00:30:17.808 --> 00:30:20.449
has an outer shell that would
be polycarbonate,

00:30:20.449 --> 00:30:23.490
so it would have reduced weight
but great strength.

00:30:23.490 --> 00:30:28.713
By the way, I really
appreciated plastic in my car

00:30:28.713 --> 00:30:31.058
about two years ago.
 

00:30:31.058 --> 00:30:34.417
I was driving down ninety-five
and I was rear ended by a maniac

00:30:34.417 --> 00:30:36.855
who was going about ninety-five
miles an hour,

00:30:36.855 --> 00:30:38.210
the police estimated.
 

00:30:38.210 --> 00:30:41.069
And I was doing about seventy
or seventy-five.

00:30:41.069 --> 00:30:45.559
But my car survived quite well.
 

00:30:45.559 --> 00:30:46.460
It's a Toyota.
 

00:30:46.460 --> 00:30:49.943
And the Toyota absorbed the
shock in the back and I

00:30:49.943 --> 00:30:54.057
fishtailed back and forth in the
passing lane and eventually

00:30:54.057 --> 00:30:55.730
brought my car over.
 

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:59.063
I got out and looked at the
back and the back end was all

00:30:59.063 --> 00:31:00.670
banged up and smashed up.
 

00:31:00.670 --> 00:31:03.916
And that's when I realized,
boy, they really have a system

00:31:03.916 --> 00:31:07.049
down here with these collapsible
bumpers where they have

00:31:07.049 --> 00:31:10.637
different kinds of plastic that
are lined up that have different

00:31:10.637 --> 00:31:14.113
degrees of hardness in them to
basically distribute the energy

00:31:14.113 --> 00:31:15.308
from a crash.
 

00:31:15.308 --> 00:31:20.166
So the use of plastic compounds
for their lightness,

00:31:20.166 --> 00:31:24.643
for their energy conservation,
for their safety,

00:31:24.643 --> 00:31:29.118
it is clearly growing in public
acceptance.

00:31:29.118 --> 00:31:32.059
Think also about other
recreational equipment.

00:31:32.059 --> 00:31:34.380
Many of you may have a Camelbak.
 

00:31:34.380 --> 00:31:35.788
What's in a Camelbak anyway?
 

00:31:35.788 --> 00:31:39.636
Well, it's a plastic bladder
made from polyurethane,

00:31:39.636 --> 00:31:43.410
but it contains no bisphenol-A
or no phthalates.

00:31:43.410 --> 00:31:45.759
There is an antimicrobial
silver lining.

00:31:45.759 --> 00:31:48.913
So when people started
realizing that they didn't want

00:31:48.913 --> 00:31:51.839
to buy the sport bottles,
such as Nalgene because of

00:31:51.839 --> 00:31:54.013
bisphenol-A,
Camelbak was quite fortunate

00:31:54.013 --> 00:31:56.308
that they had chosen a different
material.

00:31:56.308 --> 00:31:59.335
And think about stainless steel
bottles, such as these Klean

00:31:59.335 --> 00:31:59.900
Kanteens.
 

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:03.830
These are not lined with an
epoxy resin that contains

00:32:03.830 --> 00:32:04.890
bisphenol-A.
 

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:09.308
And I told you the story about
my own well water.

00:32:09.308 --> 00:32:12.923
But this is a good example here
of a tank that also has a-- this

00:32:12.923 --> 00:32:14.130
is my water supply.
 

00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:18.400
A tank that has an epoxy resin
coating on the inside,

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:20.170
and then over here on the
right-hand side,

00:32:20.170 --> 00:32:22.046
you can see that canister,
that water filter that I was

00:32:22.046 --> 00:32:23.019
describing to you earlier.
 

00:32:23.019 --> 00:32:27.940
Think about the Brita filter
system.

00:32:27.940 --> 00:32:34.685
Brita also is made out of a
plastic polycarbonate and also a

00:32:34.685 --> 00:32:35.828
styrene.
 

00:32:35.828 --> 00:32:40.450
And if you pay attention to the
Food,

00:32:40.450 --> 00:32:42.670
Drug and Cosmetic Act and the
Safe Drinking Water Act,

00:32:42.670 --> 00:32:45.217
you know that bottled water
curiously is under the

00:32:45.217 --> 00:32:47.920
jurisdiction of the Food and
Drug Administration,

00:32:47.920 --> 00:32:50.838
whereas EPA is responsible for
tap water.

00:32:50.838 --> 00:32:52.298
That really doesn't make a
whole lot of sense.

00:32:52.298 --> 00:32:55.306
There's a separate set of
compounds that one might expect

00:32:55.306 --> 00:32:58.976
in bottled water,
based upon the potential for

00:32:58.976 --> 00:33:04.170
the compounds to leach from the
plastic into the water.

00:33:04.170 --> 00:33:09.180
So overall, the plastic problem
is that it surrounds us,

00:33:09.180 --> 00:33:11.116
we live in it,
we eat from it,

00:33:11.116 --> 00:33:12.844
we drink it,
we play with it,

00:33:12.844 --> 00:33:14.430
we work with it,
we listen to it,

00:33:14.430 --> 00:33:16.480
we watch it, we cook in it.
 

00:33:16.480 --> 00:33:21.009
So where is this material going
in the environment?

00:33:21.009 --> 00:33:24.185
For one of the phthalates,
the DEHP I mentioned earlier,

00:33:24.185 --> 00:33:27.479
here's an example of mean
concentrations detectable now in

00:33:27.479 --> 00:33:28.750
the environmental.
 

00:33:28.750 --> 00:33:30.640
It's detectable in surface
water.

00:33:30.640 --> 00:33:32.740
It's detected in ground water.
 

00:33:32.740 --> 00:33:34.710
It's detected in drinking water.
 

00:33:34.710 --> 00:33:39.242
It's in sediments in the
bottoms of lakes as well as

00:33:39.242 --> 00:33:41.109
streams and rivers.
 

00:33:41.109 --> 00:33:43.130
It's found commonly in soils.
 

00:33:43.130 --> 00:33:45.730
It's found especially in soils
that are beneath landfills.

00:33:45.730 --> 00:33:48.440
So when we buried the plastic
material,

00:33:48.440 --> 00:33:52.358
nobody thought about how bad
the soil contamination might

00:33:52.358 --> 00:33:53.671
get,
how concentrated,

00:33:53.671 --> 00:33:56.376
and where it might migrate and
could it get down into the

00:33:56.376 --> 00:33:57.440
underlying aquifer.
 

00:33:57.440 --> 00:34:02.568
It's found in indoor air,
109 nanograms per cubic meter.

00:34:02.568 --> 00:34:05.355
It's found in outdoor air,
which to me is really quite

00:34:05.355 --> 00:34:06.038
surprising.
 

00:34:06.038 --> 00:34:08.612
Again, this is a function of
the sensitivity of the detection

00:34:08.612 --> 00:34:09.170
technology.
 

00:34:09.170 --> 00:34:12.329
But this is really quite a
comment on our neglect of

00:34:12.329 --> 00:34:15.800
chemicals and misunderstanding
their movement through the

00:34:15.800 --> 00:34:18.280
environment and their ultimate
fate.

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:21.150
It's detectable inside in house
dust.

00:34:21.150 --> 00:34:22.699
It's detectable in waste water.
 

00:34:22.699 --> 00:34:24.260
That should be no surprise.
 

00:34:24.260 --> 00:34:25.768
And why would that be?
 

00:34:25.768 --> 00:34:29.016
Well, my gosh,
I mean, we're feeding ourselves

00:34:29.016 --> 00:34:32.840
with water that's coming in
pipes that are made out of

00:34:32.840 --> 00:34:35.543
plastics,
and then we're disposing of

00:34:35.543 --> 00:34:39.059
waste, the drainpipes themselves
are polyvinylchloride.

00:34:39.059 --> 00:34:43.090
So why wouldn't you find
residues in the waste water?

00:34:43.090 --> 00:34:47.018
And for me in one way this is
maybe the most disturbing,

00:34:47.018 --> 00:34:49.826
it's in the rainwater,
so that it's detectable in

00:34:49.826 --> 00:34:53.451
rainwater just the same way that
strontium-90 was detectable in

00:34:53.451 --> 00:34:54.268
rainwater.
 

00:34:54.268 --> 00:34:59.465
So here's a case where we've
got an industry that basically

00:34:59.465 --> 00:35:05.469
has a legal framework that most
of the other chemical companies,

00:35:05.469 --> 00:35:07.989
like tobacco,
pesticides, pharmaceutical

00:35:07.989 --> 00:35:11.179
companies,
I mean, they would kill to have

00:35:11.179 --> 00:35:15.349
a legal license such as is being
enjoyed by the plastics

00:35:15.349 --> 00:35:16.260
industry.
 

00:35:16.260 --> 00:35:21.570
This is an example of serious
failure,

00:35:21.570 --> 00:35:23.559
and it would be a really
interesting kind of a

00:35:23.559 --> 00:35:26.259
longer-term research project if
anybody's looking for a senior

00:35:26.259 --> 00:35:28.250
essay down the road to ask the
question,

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:31.650
especially if you're interested
in political science,

00:35:31.650 --> 00:35:35.585
why wouldn't this industry be
more heavily regulated than it

00:35:35.585 --> 00:35:35.920
is?
 

00:35:35.920 --> 00:35:37.469
How did they escape control?
 

00:35:37.469 --> 00:35:39.710
How do they fly underneath the
radar screen?

00:35:39.710 --> 00:35:42.760
Again, I'm reminded of Dustin
Hoffman's film,

00:35:42.760 --> 00:35:47.197
The Graduate,
where a middle-aged guy walks

00:35:47.197 --> 00:35:52.268
up to Dustin Hoffman and pulls
him aside at a party where

00:35:52.268 --> 00:35:57.429
Mrs. Robinson is hovering
around in the background next to

00:35:57.429 --> 00:35:58.969
the pool.
 

00:35:58.969 --> 00:36:02.413
And he walks up and he says,
"I have one word for you,

00:36:02.413 --> 00:36:02.769
son.
 

00:36:02.769 --> 00:36:04.449
And it's plastics."
 

00:36:04.449 --> 00:36:06.800
Now this was back in the
mid-1960s.

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:10.715
So that we've had this
explosion of an industry that's

00:36:10.715 --> 00:36:15.000
gotten into hundreds of
thousands of different products.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.175
The chemicals,
plastic chemicals have gotten

00:36:17.175 --> 00:36:19.653
into the products,
they've made their way into our

00:36:19.653 --> 00:36:20.110
life.
 

00:36:20.110 --> 00:36:23.923
And most of us have recognized
what's plastic and generally

00:36:23.923 --> 00:36:24.780
what's not.
 

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:27.266
But we really haven't thought
about what it might mean for

00:36:27.266 --> 00:36:29.230
either our health or
environmental quality.

00:36:29.230 --> 00:36:32.891
So I want to spend just a
couple of minutes having you

00:36:32.891 --> 00:36:36.690
think about the hormonal
question that's being raised by

00:36:36.690 --> 00:36:37.590
plastics.
 

00:36:37.590 --> 00:36:43.827
And this was first recognized
by Rachel Carson when she wrote

00:36:43.827 --> 00:36:47.570
Silent Spring back in
1962.

00:36:47.570 --> 00:36:50.780
And I've mentioned this on
occasions before,

00:36:50.780 --> 00:36:53.010
but not with respect to
hormonally active compounds,

00:36:53.010 --> 00:36:58.110
where she discovered along with
colleagues that exposure to a

00:36:58.110 --> 00:37:03.128
variety of pesticides that where
hormonally active prevented

00:37:03.128 --> 00:37:06.190
calcium metabolism in eggshells.
 

00:37:06.190 --> 00:37:10.362
So that it caused reproductive
failure in certain species,

00:37:10.362 --> 00:37:12.340
especially large raptors.
 

00:37:12.340 --> 00:37:16.362
Well that concept--that we need
to worry about reproductive

00:37:16.362 --> 00:37:19.000
effects of some of these
chemicals--

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:22.034
it really escaped much
attention on the part of

00:37:22.034 --> 00:37:26.059
government through the majority
of the '60s and 1970s and then

00:37:26.059 --> 00:37:26.719
1980s.
 

00:37:26.719 --> 00:37:29.119
And then in 1996,
Theo Colburn,

00:37:29.119 --> 00:37:33.518
who also is a wildlife
ecologist like Rachel Carson,

00:37:33.518 --> 00:37:36.347
wrote Our Stolen Future.
So if you're interested in this

00:37:36.347 --> 00:37:39.094
history,
I would encourage you to read

00:37:39.094 --> 00:37:43.585
Our Stolen Future. It's
written as kind of a mystery

00:37:43.585 --> 00:37:45.525
story,
a scientific detective story

00:37:45.525 --> 00:37:46.690
they say in their subtitle.
 

00:37:46.690 --> 00:37:50.048
But she wrote this with Diane
Dumanowski, a longtime reporter

00:37:50.048 --> 00:37:52.568
with the Boston Globe,
and John Meyers,

00:37:52.568 --> 00:37:54.639
who also is a wildlife
ecologist.

00:37:54.639 --> 00:37:59.262
If you want to follow this in
more detail, I recommend Ted

00:37:59.262 --> 00:38:03.965
Shettler's and Gina Solomon's
book called Generations at

00:38:03.965 --> 00:38:05.018
Risk.
 

00:38:05.018 --> 00:38:08.773
So thinking about how our
fertility might be affected by

00:38:08.773 --> 00:38:11.436
these chemicals,
that we're experiencing

00:38:11.436 --> 00:38:15.260
mixtures without our knowledge,
without our consent.

00:38:15.260 --> 00:38:18.980
This is really the subject of
most of these books.

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:22.097
So I want to look more
carefully at one of these

00:38:22.097 --> 00:38:23.878
compounds,
bisphenol-A,

00:38:23.878 --> 00:38:27.940
because it's one that I think
almost everybody now has

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:31.389
detectable levels of BPA in
their tissues.

00:38:31.389 --> 00:38:34.110
And it's now recognized to
leach from containers.

00:38:34.110 --> 00:38:36.369
It's in soils and surface water
and fish.

00:38:36.369 --> 00:38:40.289
And it's highest in kids aged
one to six.

00:38:40.289 --> 00:38:42.340
Now that's really pretty
curious.

00:38:42.340 --> 00:38:45.780
Why would it be highest in kids
ages one to six?

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:50.275
Experts inside EPA and FDA now
believe that food and beverages

00:38:50.275 --> 00:38:53.150
are the dominant sources of
exposure.

00:38:53.150 --> 00:38:56.844
By the way, there is yet no
good answer to the question why

00:38:56.844 --> 00:38:59.139
the kids are more heavily
exposed.

00:38:59.139 --> 00:39:02.974
The effects in animals include
female reproductive tract

00:39:02.974 --> 00:39:07.500
abnormalities,
including abnormalities in the

00:39:07.500 --> 00:39:13.847
ovary and abnormalities of the
reproductive tract in older

00:39:13.847 --> 00:39:20.639
female mice and changed vaginal
morphology among post-pubertal

00:39:20.639 --> 00:39:22.309
offspring.
 

00:39:22.309 --> 00:39:26.182
And it also influences the male
reproductive system in different

00:39:26.182 --> 00:39:27.983
species,
including reduced sperm

00:39:27.983 --> 00:39:31.340
production,
reduced mice testes weight and

00:39:31.340 --> 00:39:34.059
enhanced anogenital distance.
 

00:39:34.059 --> 00:39:39.512
It also has been shown to
induce mammary gland development

00:39:39.512 --> 00:39:40.469
in mice.
 

00:39:40.469 --> 00:39:43.539
So thinking about this chemical
and thinking about the different

00:39:43.539 --> 00:39:46.561
decision making standards that
exist in different environmental

00:39:46.561 --> 00:39:50.385
laws that we've got,
I'm curious about this in that

00:39:50.385 --> 00:39:54.380
in bisphenol-A were being sold
as a biocide,

00:39:54.380 --> 00:39:57.378
as a pesticide,
the EPA could not possibly

00:39:57.378 --> 00:39:59.719
license this chemical for use.
 

00:39:59.719 --> 00:40:03.063
The persistence of the
chemical, its environmental

00:40:03.063 --> 00:40:04.969
fate,
its threat to health as

00:40:04.969 --> 00:40:08.750
evidenced by these studies would
be significant enough to prevent

00:40:08.750 --> 00:40:10.110
that from happening.
 

00:40:10.110 --> 00:40:13.777
It's also been associated more
recently with insulin

00:40:13.777 --> 00:40:17.159
resistance, raising questions
about diabetes.

00:40:17.159 --> 00:40:20.487
And also, there is some
evidence of impaired immune

00:40:20.487 --> 00:40:21.219
function.
 

00:40:21.219 --> 00:40:24.355
Now think about the fact that
we're all being exposed to

00:40:24.355 --> 00:40:27.431
hormonally active chemicals and
mixtures without really

00:40:27.431 --> 00:40:28.630
understanding it.
 

00:40:28.630 --> 00:40:32.190
We don't really know what the
intensity of our exposure is.

00:40:32.190 --> 00:40:36.068
So what are we seeing out there
in terms of fertility or

00:40:36.068 --> 00:40:38.679
diseases of reproduction in
humans?

00:40:38.679 --> 00:40:42.110
Well, we're seeing a rise in
the prevalence of infertility,

00:40:42.110 --> 00:40:44.889
a serious rise over the past
several decades.

00:40:44.889 --> 00:40:51.320
And we're also seeing a rise in
some negative effects in humans,

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:55.230
in males, particularly in young
males,

00:40:55.230 --> 00:41:00.394
increase in hypospadias,
which means that the opening of

00:41:00.394 --> 00:41:05.280
the penis does not occur at the
end of the penis,

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:06.539
it occurs further up the shaft.
 

00:41:06.539 --> 00:41:10.789
And also cryptorchidism,
which means that little kids

00:41:10.789 --> 00:41:15.449
don't have fully descended
testicles when they're born.

00:41:15.449 --> 00:41:19.074
So that there are a variety of
different reproductive problems

00:41:19.074 --> 00:41:22.880
occurring in the population at
higher incidence than formerly.

00:41:22.880 --> 00:41:26.407
Well, it's curious when a
debate like this occurs,

00:41:26.407 --> 00:41:29.719
when a product is out there on
the marketplace,

00:41:29.719 --> 00:41:33.320
it's treated globally,
what do we do about it?

00:41:33.320 --> 00:41:36.416
Well, the government,
the regulatory agencies tend to

00:41:36.416 --> 00:41:38.920
call in experts and get expert
opinions.

00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:44.409
So the National Institute for
Environmental Health Sciences,

00:41:44.409 --> 00:41:48.688
NIEHS, convened a panel,
it turned out the panel was put

00:41:48.688 --> 00:41:53.512
together and some of the reading
materials were put together by

00:41:53.512 --> 00:41:58.103
some representatives of the
industry itself so that many had

00:41:58.103 --> 00:42:02.925
a view that this was not really
an independent analysis of what

00:42:02.925 --> 00:42:06.349
the effects of bisphenol-A might
be.

00:42:06.349 --> 00:42:09.289
And they concluded with a
phrase "That there is some

00:42:09.289 --> 00:42:12.230
concern that exposure to
bisphenol-A causes some of these

00:42:12.230 --> 00:42:13.909
reproductive problems."
 

00:42:13.909 --> 00:42:17.875
A second panel was convened of
independent scientists that had

00:42:17.875 --> 00:42:21.579
no connections to the plastics
industry or the bisphenol-A

00:42:21.579 --> 00:42:22.880
industry at all.
 

00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:25.250
And they concluded something
quite different.

00:42:25.250 --> 00:42:28.293
"The wide range of adverse
effects of low doses of BPA in

00:42:28.293 --> 00:42:31.438
laboratory animals exposed both
during development and adulthood

00:42:31.438 --> 00:42:34.184
is a source for concern with
regard to the potential for

00:42:34.184 --> 00:42:36.480
similar adverse effects in
humans."

00:42:36.480 --> 00:42:40.989
So that this idea that you take
a question of science and you

00:42:40.989 --> 00:42:45.425
raise it in front of a group of
experts really forces one to

00:42:45.425 --> 00:42:49.934
think carefully about what the
conflicts of interest might be

00:42:49.934 --> 00:42:51.739
for those experts.
 

00:42:51.739 --> 00:42:54.773
How could you put together a
committee that clearly was

00:42:54.773 --> 00:42:55.559
independent?
 

00:42:55.559 --> 00:42:57.880
Well, full disclosure is one
way of doing that.

00:42:57.880 --> 00:43:01.617
So that demanding the people
disclose their income tax

00:43:01.617 --> 00:43:05.639
records or disclose their
affiliations or their consulting

00:43:05.639 --> 00:43:09.800
relationships with different
industries could clarify in the

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:14.032
public's mind whether or not
there is a high probability of a

00:43:14.032 --> 00:43:14.949
bias.
 

00:43:14.949 --> 00:43:17.965
Well, remember what I said
about bisphenol-A being the

00:43:17.965 --> 00:43:19.556
hardener,
the phthalate,

00:43:19.556 --> 00:43:22.666
DEHP is a softener,
it's produced in a much lower

00:43:22.666 --> 00:43:25.530
volume,
260 million pounds per year.

00:43:25.530 --> 00:43:27.179
It's also found in our bodies.
 

00:43:27.179 --> 00:43:29.030
It's added to PVC plastic.
 

00:43:29.030 --> 00:43:33.829
And its recycling percentage is
close to zero.

00:43:33.829 --> 00:43:36.619
And it also is widely found in
the environment.

00:43:36.619 --> 00:43:41.347
And it's been found with
similar kinds of adverse effects

00:43:41.347 --> 00:43:45.483
in males, in test animals,
including reduced sperm

00:43:45.483 --> 00:43:49.030
production and early onset of
puberty.

00:43:49.030 --> 00:43:53.224
And all of this exposure is
coming predominately because of

00:43:53.224 --> 00:43:56.768
the failure of the Toxic
Substance Control Act.

00:43:56.768 --> 00:44:00.092
So Congress really recognized
that we needed to test these

00:44:00.092 --> 00:44:03.766
chemicals before they made their
way into the market back in the

00:44:03.766 --> 00:44:04.699
early 1970s.
 

00:44:04.699 --> 00:44:08.980
So they passed TSCA and gave
the authority to EPA to demand

00:44:08.980 --> 00:44:10.530
pre-market testing.
 

00:44:10.530 --> 00:44:12.929
But they didn't do anything
about it.

00:44:12.929 --> 00:44:15.764
So again, the universe of
chemicals is big,

00:44:15.764 --> 00:44:19.141
82,000 chemicals traded in
commerce, they have some

00:44:19.141 --> 00:44:20.559
commercial value.
 

00:44:20.559 --> 00:44:23.630
About 20,000 of those were
added since 1986.

00:44:23.630 --> 00:44:26.010
And what that means is that
this statute,

00:44:26.010 --> 00:44:28.791
the way it's worded,
it granted exemptions as

00:44:28.791 --> 00:44:31.826
chemicals that were
grandfathered or protected in

00:44:31.826 --> 00:44:35.365
the marketplace that couldn't be
removed by EPA to 62,000

00:44:35.365 --> 00:44:37.010
different compounds.
 

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:41.155
The statute is unusual also
because it places a high burden

00:44:41.155 --> 00:44:45.588
on EPA to demonstrate that there
is a significant danger before

00:44:45.588 --> 00:44:50.380
it can demand from the industry
that they produce the evidence.

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:53.806
Now, just pharmaceuticals and
like pesticides and other

00:44:53.806 --> 00:44:56.090
products that we've talked
about,

00:44:56.090 --> 00:44:59.469
how much sense does it make to
have the industry producing the

00:44:59.469 --> 00:45:02.349
data themselves and then
presenting their case to the

00:45:02.349 --> 00:45:05.119
Environmental Protection Agency
for licensing?

00:45:05.119 --> 00:45:07.260
Where should this occur?
 

00:45:07.260 --> 00:45:10.760
Should there be some sort of an
independent organization set up

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:13.639
that would be more protected
from potential bias?

00:45:13.639 --> 00:45:16.052
Well clearly,
there's an economic stake

00:45:16.052 --> 00:45:19.610
involved, and industry is
anxious to spend that money.

00:45:19.610 --> 00:45:22.538
But this high burden on EPA to
demonstrate danger is the

00:45:22.538 --> 00:45:25.733
primary reason for the failure
of the Toxic Substance Control

00:45:25.733 --> 00:45:26.159
Act.
 

00:45:26.159 --> 00:45:30.766
So that over this period of
time, they have demanded testing

00:45:30.766 --> 00:45:33.500
for only 200 different
chemicals.

00:45:33.500 --> 00:45:37.010
And out of those 200,
only five have been prohibited.

00:45:37.010 --> 00:45:40.851
So what are states and other
governmental agencies doing

00:45:40.851 --> 00:45:41.760
about this?
 

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:44.920
Well, a variety of state
initiatives, including here in

00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:46.909
Connecticut, have been launched.
 

00:45:46.909 --> 00:45:49.572
And a number of us have been
involved in drafting legislation

00:45:49.572 --> 00:45:50.550
in different states.
 

00:45:50.550 --> 00:45:54.483
But here in Connecticut,
we now have a statute on the

00:45:54.483 --> 00:45:58.568
books as of last year that
requires that bisphenol-A be

00:45:58.568 --> 00:46:02.954
taken out of products that are
intended to be used by young

00:46:02.954 --> 00:46:04.090
children.
 

00:46:04.090 --> 00:46:07.989
And similar statutes have been
passed in these other states.

00:46:07.989 --> 00:46:12.500
You can think about regulatory
policy being of testing a

00:46:12.500 --> 00:46:17.666
chemical, figuring how dangerous
it is and then figuring out how

00:46:17.666 --> 00:46:19.800
you might regulate it.
 

00:46:19.800 --> 00:46:21.500
Or you might just say,
here's a clear threshold.

00:46:21.500 --> 00:46:25.719
If a chemical behaves in this
way, say it's persistent,

00:46:25.719 --> 00:46:28.139
it's bioaccumulative,
it's found in human tissues,

00:46:28.139 --> 00:46:31.159
and it's demonstrated to be
hormonally active,

00:46:31.159 --> 00:46:32.690
that that's it.
 

00:46:32.690 --> 00:46:33.880
It's out of the marketplace.
 

00:46:33.880 --> 00:46:35.320
That's a prohibitive policy.
 

00:46:35.320 --> 00:46:38.960
So once you decide not to
employ a prohibitive policy,

00:46:38.960 --> 00:46:43.177
once you decide not to ban,
you basically require the

00:46:43.177 --> 00:46:47.882
regulatory agency to figure out
exactly which uses would be

00:46:47.882 --> 00:46:50.480
allowed and which would not.
 

00:46:50.480 --> 00:46:53.110
And it creates a very expensive
and difficult,

00:46:53.110 --> 00:46:56.326
time consuming monitoring and
enforcement problem for an

00:46:56.326 --> 00:46:56.969
agency.
 

00:46:56.969 --> 00:47:01.402
So the regulation--chemical by
chemical, use by use--is not

00:47:01.402 --> 00:47:06.219
likely to have much effect in
solving a problem such as this.

00:47:06.219 --> 00:47:10.771
California is requiring a
listing of DEHP under its

00:47:10.771 --> 00:47:12.320
Proposition 65.
 

00:47:12.320 --> 00:47:15.659
And this was required in 2008.
 

00:47:15.659 --> 00:47:20.427
And what it's done is,
it's limited the concentration

00:47:20.427 --> 00:47:24.829
of DEHP in products to less than
0.01 percent.

00:47:24.829 --> 00:47:26.250
Now what would that do?
 

00:47:26.250 --> 00:47:30.985
You're going to limit the
concentration of a chemical in a

00:47:30.985 --> 00:47:33.230
product to 0.012 percent.
 

00:47:33.230 --> 00:47:35.960
It's going to force the
government into becoming a

00:47:35.960 --> 00:47:37.409
monitoring organization.
 

00:47:37.409 --> 00:47:40.862
So it's got to go out and it's
got to test in order to find

00:47:40.862 --> 00:47:42.650
products that do not comply.
 

00:47:42.650 --> 00:47:44.940
Again, very expensive,
and a strategy that's not

00:47:44.940 --> 00:47:45.768
likely to work.
 

00:47:45.768 --> 00:47:48.668
Now, the European Union is
taking a very different

00:47:48.668 --> 00:47:49.320
approach.
 

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:55.550
They have adopted a law in 2006
known as REACH.

00:47:55.550 --> 00:47:59.251
And REACH requires toxicity and
environmental fate testing for

00:47:59.251 --> 00:48:01.739
1,500 of the highest volume
chemicals,

00:48:01.739 --> 00:48:07.963
the highest amount produced
among the 80,000 chemicals that

00:48:07.963 --> 00:48:12.150
are out there that are poorly
tested.

00:48:12.150 --> 00:48:16.150
It's also a program that's been
delayed.

00:48:16.150 --> 00:48:21.829
The endocrine screening program
will not begin until 2012.

00:48:21.829 --> 00:48:23.630
The mixture problem remains.
 

00:48:23.630 --> 00:48:27.201
They still are not going to
tackle the issue that we're

00:48:27.201 --> 00:48:31.170
exposed in mixtures that might
act via the same mechanism.

00:48:31.170 --> 00:48:33.550
And also, they will be
grandfathering many of the

00:48:33.550 --> 00:48:36.329
chemicals that are produced in
the smaller quantities.

00:48:36.329 --> 00:48:40.402
But why would it not make sense
to focus exclusively on the

00:48:40.402 --> 00:48:42.860
high-production volume
chemicals?

00:48:42.860 --> 00:48:46.096
Well, you've got to think about
the fact that there could be

00:48:46.096 --> 00:48:49.003
some chemicals that are
extremely potent and extremely

00:48:49.003 --> 00:48:50.760
dangerous at very low doses.
 

00:48:50.760 --> 00:48:53.909
So plutonium again is a good
example of that.

00:48:53.909 --> 00:48:56.246
Also, corporations are acting
on their own,

00:48:56.246 --> 00:48:59.695
so that PVC corporate phase-out
policies have been adopted by a

00:48:59.695 --> 00:49:01.809
variety of firms,
including these.

00:49:01.809 --> 00:49:04.400
And this is having a very
significant effect.

00:49:04.400 --> 00:49:06.159
Number one, it's educating a
lot of people.

00:49:06.159 --> 00:49:09.449
When they see a label that says
PVC free or BPA free,

00:49:09.449 --> 00:49:12.297
they start to pay attention and
ask questions,

00:49:12.297 --> 00:49:13.690
why that might be.
 

00:49:13.690 --> 00:49:17.451
And I want you to back up and I
want you to think about really

00:49:17.451 --> 00:49:19.610
what the core of this problem
is.

00:49:19.610 --> 00:49:24.159
It really is consumerism,
the fact that we buy much more

00:49:24.159 --> 00:49:25.400
than we need.
 

00:49:25.400 --> 00:49:28.987
We don't pay attention in a way
to the ingredients of different

00:49:28.987 --> 00:49:31.650
products that we bring into our
environment.

00:49:31.650 --> 00:49:35.512
It also has to do with the
ignorance of our effects of our

00:49:35.512 --> 00:49:36.530
own behavior.
 

00:49:36.530 --> 00:49:39.643
When I was preparing this
lecture over the past couple of

00:49:39.643 --> 00:49:42.980
days, I have to admit that I got
really angry with myself.

00:49:42.980 --> 00:49:46.068
I got angry and I got
surprised, because I think of

00:49:46.068 --> 00:49:49.219
myself as somebody that should
have known better.

00:49:49.219 --> 00:49:53.029
I should have adjusted my
lifestyle to what I recognize as

00:49:53.029 --> 00:49:56.833
a potential threat,
not just to the environment,

00:49:56.833 --> 00:50:01.610
not just to the population,
but to my own kids.

00:50:01.610 --> 00:50:05.181
So there are many reasons for
that that don't have to do with

00:50:05.181 --> 00:50:05.480
me.
 

00:50:05.480 --> 00:50:08.559
But I should have known better
than that.

00:50:08.559 --> 00:50:12.128
And hopefully after taking this
course, you will not make this

00:50:12.128 --> 00:50:13.710
kind of problem yourself.
 

00:50:13.710 --> 00:50:18.219
You can think about national
regulation as a partial solution

00:50:18.219 --> 00:50:20.699
because the markets are global.
 

00:50:20.699 --> 00:50:23.885
People are trading these
products and chemicals across

00:50:23.885 --> 00:50:25.809
national borders all the time.
 

00:50:25.809 --> 00:50:28.307
So what does it mean if the
United States passes a law,

00:50:28.307 --> 00:50:30.159
but say Germany does not pass
the law?

00:50:30.159 --> 00:50:33.029
Or Germany's got a more
restrictive statute than the

00:50:33.029 --> 00:50:33.929
United States?
 

00:50:33.929 --> 00:50:37.208
That's a recipe for trade
barriers that are likely to be

00:50:37.208 --> 00:50:38.579
eventually litigated.
 

00:50:38.579 --> 00:50:43.739
So think also about the
concentration and dispersion of

00:50:43.739 --> 00:50:49.474
products and the effect of one
corporation like McDonald's or

00:50:49.474 --> 00:50:54.920
say Toyota to make a choice that
they are going to not use

00:50:54.920 --> 00:50:57.119
certain products.
 

00:50:57.119 --> 00:50:59.728
That they're not going to
distribute a billion new toys

00:50:59.728 --> 00:51:02.289
over the next two years with
their new market line.

00:51:02.289 --> 00:51:07.585
Or that they're going to demand
ultimate accountability for the

00:51:07.585 --> 00:51:11.768
eventual fate or end of life of
their product,

00:51:11.768 --> 00:51:14.481
the way that some of the
printer companies have that have

00:51:14.481 --> 00:51:16.981
demanded the recycling,
or not demanded,

00:51:16.981 --> 00:51:21.331
but offered to take back the
ink cartridges once they are

00:51:21.331 --> 00:51:22.030
empty.
 

00:51:22.030 --> 00:51:25.195
So basically,
the government has been

00:51:25.195 --> 00:51:30.119
neglecting externalities and
there has been an absence of

00:51:30.119 --> 00:51:31.789
accountability.
 

00:51:31.789 --> 00:51:34.760
So here is a list of potential
solutions.

